melina uncapher from experience to memory the contributions of parietal attention mechanisms to memory formation department of psychology stanford university department of psychology search psychology web site melina uncapher from experience to memory the contributions of parietal attention mechanisms to memory formation navigation people research and experiments education and training events related programs resources job opportunities about us user login sunet id login home melina uncapher from experience to memory the contributions of parietal attention mechanisms to memory formation speaker melina uncapher stanford location jordan hall building 420 room 050 the formation of episodic memories memories for life events is affected by attention during event processing a leading neurobiological model of attention posits two separate yet interacting systems depend on distinct regions in the parietal lobe however the contributions of parietal attention mechanisms are relatively overlooked in neurobiological models of memory formation in this talk i will explore how parietal attention mechanisms may impact event encoding i will discuss a meta analysis of functional mri studies that document the relationship between parietal activation during encoding and subsequent memory performance eg later remembering or forgetting as well as an empirical study that directly tested the conclusions of the meta analysis i will introduce an emerging mechanistic framework that considers how parietal mediated attention mechanisms regulate encoding public access not open to the public date and time friday 29 may 2009 3 15pm 4 30pm stanford home contact us maps and directions department of psychology jordan hall building 01 420 stanford university 450 serra mall stanford ca 94305 tel 650 725 2400 fax 650 725 5699
